The paper presents a deep-learning approach to diagnosing multiple sclerosis from smartphone-derived digital biomarkers. The use of smartphone data for monitoring MS symptoms falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The paper also uses deep learning, which is a subfield of machine learning (cs.LG). The use of digital biomarkers and the analysis of long-term monitoring data could also fall under the category of cybernetics (cs.CY). Additionally, the paper uses neural networks, which is a subfield of computational neuroscience (cs.NE), and the use of deep learning for diagnosis could also fall under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
